St Charles ME(1), Sadri H, Minshall ME, Tunis SL.

Author information:
(1)IMS Health Inc., Falls Church, Virginia 22046, USA.

BACKGROUND: Patients with type 1 diabetes mellitus (DM) may be treated with 
insulin via multiple daily injections (MDI) or continuous subcutaneous insulin 
infusion (CSII).
OBJECTIVE: The purpose of this study was to evaluate the projected long-term 
cost-effectiveness of CSII compared with MDI by modeling a simulated sample of 
adult patients with type 1 DM in Canada.
METHODS: A health economic model was used to determine the incremental 
cost-effectiveness ratio (ICER) of CSII compared with MDI from the perspective 
of a Canadian provincial government. The primary input variable was change in 
glycosylated hemoglobin (HbA(1c)). A series of Markov constructs also simulated 
the progression of disease-related complications. Annual acquisition costs for 
CSII and MDI were year-2006 Can $6347.18 and Can $4649.69, respectively. A 
